answers.body_markdown:
[Constructors](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/specs/jls/se17/html/jls-8.html#jls-8.8) are special kind constructs in Java. They are not methods, they are nor members, but a special constructs that are used to initialize instances of the surrounding class.

You can identify constructor with the following parts:
- It has no return type;
- It may declare parameters, but may also be without any of them (this is called default, a.k.a. no-args constructor);
- Constructor name **must** be exactly as same as its surrounding class name;
- Constructors, in most of cases, are used to initialize member variables (fields) with `this.` prefix.

Few notes about constructors (from the JLS):
- Constructor declarations are not members. They are never inherited and therefore are not subject to hiding or overriding;
- Constructors are invoked by class instance creation expressions. E.g. if the class is `class Person`, its instance creation expression with default constructor will be `new Person();`.

For example:
```java
public class Person {

    private int age;
    private String name;

    // This is a default / no-args constructor
    public Person() {
    }

    // This is a constructor with two parameters
    public Person(int age, String name) {
        this.age = age;
        this.name = name;
    }
}

public class Main {
    
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Person p1 = new Person();
        Person p2 = new Person(15, &quot;John&quot;);
    }

}
```

